{{Infobox language |name=Badaga |nativename=படகா/ಬಡಗ |states=[[India]] |region=[[Tamil Nadu]], [[The Nilgiris District|The Nilgiris]] |ethnicity=[[Badaga people|Badaga]] |speakers=133,500 |date=2011 census |ref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011Census/Language_MTs.html|title=Statement 1: Abstract of speakers' strength of languages and mother tongues - 2011|publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|access-date=2018-07-07}}</ref> |familycolor=Dravidian |fam2=[[Southern Dravidian languages|Southern]] |fam3=[[Tamil–Kannada languages|Tamil–Kannada]] |fam4=[[Kannada–Badaga]] |iso3=bfq |glotto=bada1257 |glottorefname=Badaga |script=[[Kannada script]] [[Tamil script]]{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} |notice=IPA }}
'''Badaga''' is a southern [[Dravidian language]] spoken by approximately 135,000 people in the [[Nilgiri Hills]] of [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref name="Steever 1998">{{cite book|last=Steever|first=Sanford B.|title=The Dravidian languages|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1998|pages=6–7|isbn=978-0-415-10023-6}}</ref> It is known for its [[R-colored vowel|retroflex vowels]]. It has similarities with neighbouring [[Kannada language]] as Hale Kannada, and has now been identified as an independent language by a French linguistic scholar, Christiane Pilot-Raichoor.<ref>{{cite news | last =Thiagarajan | first =Shantha | title = Badaga language not a dialect of Kannada, claims French linguistic scholar| newspaper =The Times of India | date =4 December 2012 | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-12-04/coimbatore/35593445_1_badaga-community-nilgiris-language|accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref> The word Badaga, meaning "northerner", refers to the Badaga language as well as the [[Badagas|Badaga indigenous people]] who speak it.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=a74HA_RX3rIC&pg=PA391|title=A Badada-English Dictionary|page=391|publisher=[[Mouton de Gruyter]]|isbn=978-3110126778|year=1992|last= Hockings|first=Paul|last2=Pilot-Raichoor|first2=Christiane}}</ref>
==Phonology== Badaga has five vowels qualities, {{IPA|/i e a o u/}}, each of which may be long or short and until the 1930s were contrastively half and fully retroflexed, for a total of 30 vowel phonemes.<ref>Emenau (1931) reports no tokens of {{IPA|/i˞˞/}}, but suggests this is an accidental gap.</ref> Current speakers only distinguish retroflection for a few vowels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Badaga |publisher=UCLA Phonetics Lab |url=http://www.phonetics.ucla.edu/appendix/languages/badaga/badaga.html |accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" |- |+Example words<ref>{{cite web |title= Word List for Badaga |publisher=UCLA Phonetics Lab |url=http://archive.phonetics.ucla.edu/Language/BFQ/bfq_word-list_1992_03.html |accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref> ! IPA ! Gloss |- |{{IPA|/noː/}}||disease |- |{{IPA|/po˞˞ː/}}||scar |- |{{IPA|/mo˞e˞/}} || sprout |- |{{IPA|/a˞e˞/}} || tiger's den |- |{{IPA|/ha˞ːsu/}} ||to spread out |- |{{IPA|/ka˞˞ːʃu/}} || to remove |- |{{IPA|/i˞ːu˞˞/}} ||seven |- |{{IPA|/hu˞˞ːj/}} ||tamarind |- |{{IPA|/be˞ː/}}|| bangle |- |{{IPA|/be˞˞ː/}}||banana |- |{{IPA|/huj/}}||to strike |- |{{IPA|/hu˞j/}}|| tamarind |- |{{IPA|/u˞˞j/}} ||chisel |}
Note on transcription: rhoticity {{angbr|{{IPA|◌˞}}}} indicates half-retroflexion; doubled {{angbr|{{IPA|◌˞˞}}}} it indicates full retroflexion.
{| class="wikitable" |+ ! ! !Bilabial !Alveolar !Retroflex !Palatal !Velar |- ! rowspan="2" |Stop !{{Small|voiceless}} |p |t |ʈ |c |k |- !{{Small|[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} |b |d |ɖ |ɟ |g |- ! colspan="2" |Fricative |v |s | | | |- ! colspan="2" |Nasal |m |n |ɳ | | |- ! colspan="2" |Approximant | |l |ɻ |j | |- ! colspan="2" |Trill | |r | | | |}
==Badaga script== Several attempts were made at constructing an orthography based on [[English language|English]] and [[Kannada]]. The earliest printed book using [[Kannada script]] was a Christian work, "Anga Kartagibba Yesu Kristana Olleya Suddiya Pustaka" by Basel Mission Press of [[Mangaluru]] in 1890.<ref>http://gospelgo.com/q/Badaga%20Bible%20-%20Gospel%20of%20Luke.pdf</ref>
[[File:Badaga script- Vowels and Consonants (jeeva Swara and Dheha Swara).jpg|thumb|Usage of vowels and consonats of Tamil script resp. Kannanda script to create Badaga script]] [[File:Badaga script- Jeevadhehagalu.jpg|thumb|Usage of Tamil script resp. Kannanda script to create Badaga script]]
List of Books in Kannada Script:<ref>https://archive.org/details/kannadabadagakur00brit</ref> #Anga Kartagibba Yesu Kristana Olleya Suddiya Pustaka #Jonah #Mana Kannadi #Marka Bareda Loka ratchagana kade #Zion
The Badaga language is also written in the [[Tamil script]].
===Dictionary=== The Badaga language is well studied and several Badaga-English Dictionaries have been produced since the latter part of the nineteenth century.<ref name="dictionary">{{cite book |last1=Paul Hockings |first1=Christiane Pilot-Raichoor |title=A Badaga-English Dictionary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a74HA_RX3rIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=badaga+people&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kBwSUbyABM3JrAedzICAAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=badaga%20people&f=false |accessdate=6 February 2013 |edition=Reprint |volume= |year=1992 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |location= |language= |isbn= |page= |pages= }}</ref>
