'''Pyarimohan Acharya''' was a 19th-century historian, educationist, and public intellectual from [[Cuttack]] in the modern-day state of [[Odisha]], India. He is known for his ''Odisara Itihasa'' (History of Odisha) which was published in 1879. Pyarimohan wrote his history in response to an advertisement by the colonial government of the time looking for a textbook for use in schools. While the book was accepted by the government, its publication caused a controversy and was consequently not inducted into the school syllabus. ''Odisara Itihasa'' nevertheless acquired prominence as it was the first history textbook to be written by a native author.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Trüper|editor-first1=Henning|editor-last2=Chakrabarty|editor-first2=Dipesh|editor-last3=Subrahmanyam|editor-first3=Sanjay|last=Satpathy|first=Siddharth|title=Historical Teleologies in the Modern World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9781474221085|page=143|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=-CWCCgAAQBAJ|language=en|chapter=Reading History in Colonial India}}</ref>
