{{infobox language |name=South Bergish dialect |nativename = ''Südbergische Dialekte'' |region = Western Germany |speakers=? |familycolor = indo-european |fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] |fam3=[[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] |fam4=[[High German languages|High German]] |fam5=[[Central German]] |fam6=[[West Central German]] |fam7=[[Central Franconian]] |fam8=[[Ripuarian language|Ripuarian]] |isoexception=dialect |glotto=none }}
'''South Bergish''' (German: ''{{lang|de|Südbergische Dialekte}}'') or '''Upper Bergish''' (German: ''{{lang|de|Oberbergische Dialekte}}'') is a group of German dialects of the [[Bergisches Land|Bergisches Land Region]] East of the [[Rhine]] and approximately south of the [[Wupper]] and north of the [[Sieg]]. These dialects are part of the [[Ripuarian language|Ripuarian group]] and thus are also called East Ripuarian. Ripuarian dialects are also spoken west of the Rhine up to the German border, and in some small areas next to the respective borders in [[Belgium]] and in the [[Netherlands]]. Ripuarian Bergish dialects belong to the [[Middle High German|Middle German]] group, and thus are varieties of [[High German]], where they belong to the northmost ones. In the North, they border to the [[East Bergish]] and the West Bergish language groups, which are part of the [[Low Franconian]] group like [[Dutch language|Dutch]].
In popular view, rather than scientific, South Bergish dialects are often referred to as ''[[Bergish dialects|Bergish]]'' by locals, or as ''[[Rhinelandic]]'' by outsiders.
